Problem Context¶

Background and Context

Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Problem Statement¶

Objective

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not in the next 6 months.

Data Description¶

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle. The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc.

Data Dictionary¶

CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

Surname: Last name of the customer

CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

Geography: A customer’s location

Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

Age: Age of the customer

Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

NumOfProducts: It refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

Balance: Account balance

HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable that decides whether the customer has a credit card or not.

EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

IsActiveMember: It is a categorical variable that decides whether the customer is an active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions, etc )

Exited: It is a categorical variable that decides whether the customer left the bank within six months or not. It can take two values

0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank )

1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

# function to create barplots with percentages labled on the bars


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 3))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 3))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot stacked bar chart
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 6))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

What is feature scaling?

Feature scaling is a class of statistical techniques that, as the name implies, scales the features of our data so that they all have a similar range.

If you have multiple independent variables like age, salary, and height, with their range as (18–100 Years), (25,000–75,000 Euros), and (1–2 Meters) respectively, feature scaling would help them all to be in the same range.

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation

Model evaluation criterion

Model can make wrong predictions as:

Predicting that a customer will leave and the customer stays with bank.

Predicting that customer will stay, but the customer actually leaves the bank.

Which case is more important? Predicting that customer will stay, but customer actually leaves. This will cause the bank to loose customers and business. Also the marketing and promotional effort will not be made towards retaining these customers.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negative? The company would want the recall to be maximized. Greater the recall score, higher are the chances of minimizing the False Negatives.

BottomLine - We want the False Negatives to be at a minimum.

Building a very basic Artificial Neural Network - Model 1¶

Model1 will be configured with the following:

  • 3 layers - relu activation function for the hidden layer and sigmoid activation for the output layer.
  • Stochastic Gradient Descent with the default learning rate as our optimizer
  • Threshold will be hard-coded to 0.5

The neural network will be configured to take in a vector of length 13 as input. For each transaction, the final layer will output a probability.

#Function to generate the confusion matrix
def make_confusion_matrix(cf,
                          group_names=None,
                          categories='auto',
                          count=True,
                          percent=True,
                          cbar=True,
                          xyticks=True,
                          xyplotlabels=True,
                          sum_stats=True,
                          figsize=None,
                          cmap='Blues',
                          title=None):
    '''
    This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cm using a Seaborn heatmap visualization.
    Arguments
    '''


    # CODE TO GENERATE TEXT INSIDE EACH SQUARE
    blanks = ['' for i in range(cf.size)]

    if group_names and len(group_names)==cf.size:
        group_labels = ["{}\n".format(value) for value in group_names]
    else:
        group_labels = blanks

    if count:
        group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    else:
        group_counts = blanks

    if percent:
        group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    else:
        group_percentages = blanks

    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])


    # CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
    if sum_stats:
        #Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
        accuracy  = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))



    # SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
    if figsize==None:
        #Get default figure size if not set
        figsize = plt.rcParams.get('figure.figsize')

    if xyticks==False:
        #Do not show categories if xyticks is False
        categories=False


    # MAKE THE HEATMAP VISUALIZATION
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(cf,annot=box_labels,fmt="",cmap=cmap,cbar=cbar,xticklabels=categories,yticklabels=categories)

    
    if title:
        plt.title(title)
In [133]:
#Function to draw the AUC-ROC curve and update the predictions based on the best threshold
def draw_roc_curve(y_predictions):

  # calculate roc curves
  fpr, tpr, thresholds1 = roc_curve(y_test, y_predictions)
  # calculate the g-mean for each threshold
  gmeans1 = np.sqrt(tpr * (1-fpr))
  # locate the index of the largest g-mean
  ix = np.argmax(gmeans1)
  print('Best Threshold=%f, G-Mean=%.3f' % (thresholds1[ix], gmeans1[ix]))
  # plot the roc curve for the model
  pyplot.plot([0,1], [0,1], linestyle='--', label='No Skill')
  pyplot.plot(fpr, tpr, marker='.')
  pyplot.scatter(fpr[ix], tpr[ix], marker='o', color='black', label='Best')
  # axis labels
  pyplot.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
  pyplot.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
  pyplot.legend()
  # show the plot
  pyplot.show()
  for i in range(len(y_test)):
    if y_predictions[i]>thresholds1[ix]:
        y_predictions[i]=1 
    else:
        y_predictions[i]=0
  return y_predictions

As you can see, the above model has a low recall value of 0.45. The imbalanced dataset could be contributing to the poor recall value.

In Model 1, we hardcoded the threshold to 0.5. Given the imbalanced dataset, we will benefit from using the ROC-AUC to determine the optimal threshold.

For the next model, let us change the optimizer, tune the decision threshold, utilize the Dropout technique to increase the model performance

Model 2¶

Model2 will be configured with the following:

  • 3 layers - relu activation function for the hidden layer and sigmoid activation for the output layer.
  • Adam Optimizer with a learning rate of 0.001
  • Threshold will be determined using the ROC-AUC curve
  • Dropout technique will be utilized - Dropout(0.5)
  • batch_size=128

The neural network will be configured to take in a vector of length 13 as input. For each transaction, the final layer will output a probability.

# First hidden layer with 32 neurons and relu activation function
model_2.add(Dense(32, activation='relu',kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))
model_2.add(Dropout(0.5))

# Output layer - We use the sigmoid because we want probability outcomes - binary classification
model_2.add(Dense(1,activation='sigmoid'))

Model 3¶

Model3 will be configured with the following:

  • 5 layers - relu activation function for the hidden layer and sigmoid activation for the output layer. (Model 1 & 2 had only 3 layers)
  • Adam Optimizer with a learning rate of 0.01 (Model 2 had a 0.001 learning rate)
  • Threshold will be determined using the ROC-AUC curve
  • Both Dropout and BatchNormalization techniques will be utilized. (Model 2 used the Dropout technique alone)
  • batch_size=128

The neural network will be configured to take in a vector of length 13 as input. For each transaction, the final layer will output a probability.

set_seed_and_clear_session()
In [158]:
# Initializing the ANN
# We will be adding the layers sequentially
model_3 = Sequential()

#This adds the input layer with 256 neurons with the relu activation function, the input shape tuple denotes the number of predictors
model_3.add(Dense(256, activation='relu',kernel_initializer='he_uniform',input_shape=(13,)))

model_3.add(Dropout(0.5))

# First hidden layer with 128 neurons and relu activation function
model_3.add(Dense(128, activation='relu',kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))

model_3.add(Dropout(0.5))

# Second hidden layer with 64 neurons and relu activation function
model_3.add(Dense(64, activation='relu',kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))

model_3.add(BatchNormalization())

# Third hidden layer with 32 neurons and relu activation function
model_3.add(Dense(32, activation='relu',kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))

# Output layer - We use the sigmoid because we want probability outcomes - binary classification
model_3.add(Dense(1,activation='sigmoid'))

Model 4 - Using GridSearchCV¶

Some important hyperparameters to look out for while optimizing neural networks are:

Type of Architecture

Number of Layers

Number of Neurons in a layer

Regularization hyperparameters

Learning Rate

Type of Optimizer

Dropout Rate

We will use GridSearchCV to optimize two hyperparameters - Batch Size & Learning Rate.

Model4 will be configured with the following:

  • 7 layers - relu activation function for the hidden layer and sigmoid
    activation for the output layer.

  • Adam Optimizer

  • Threshold will be determined using the ROC-AUC curve

  • Both Dropout and BatchNormalization techniques will be utilized.

The neural network will be configured to take in a vector of length 13 as input. For each transaction, the final layer will output a probability.

In [168]:
set_seed_and_clear_session()
In [169]:
def create_model_v4(lr,batch_size):  
    model_4 = Sequential()
    model_4.add(Dense(256,activation='relu',input_dim = X_train.shape[1]))
    model_4.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model_4.add(Dense(128,activation='relu'))
    model_4.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model_4.add(Dense(128,activation='relu'))
    model_4.add(BatchNormalization())
    model_4.add(Dense(64,activation='relu'))
    model_4.add(BatchNormalization())
    model_4.add(Dense(64,activation='relu'))
    model_4.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model_4.add(Dense(32,activation='relu')) 
    model_4.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

    #compile model
    optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr)
    model_4.compile(optimizer = optimizer,loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['accuracy'])
    return model_4

Model Performance Evaluation

When it comes to loss and accuracy, all the 4 models yeilded approximately the same values - loss between 0.35-0.36 and accuracy between 0.85-0.86.

Taking the recall metric into consideration, Model2 is a clear winner by offering a recall value of 0.80. Model2 had good accuracy and loss graphs for both the training and validation datasets and it generalized well.

Recommendation to the bank is to use Model2 for future analysis and identifying the customers that are most likely to leave the bank.

Conclusion

We conducted Exploratory Data Analysis and noted the trends and patterns. We identified that

  • Customers who purchased 3 or 4 products are more likely to leave the bank
  • Customers in the age group of 40 to 60 are more likely to leave the bank
  • Female customers seem to be leaving the bank more than their male counter parts.
  • Customers based in Germany are exiting the bank compared to the customers based in France and Spain.
  • Customers who are actively using the bank services are less likely to exit.
  • The average balance of the attrited customers is slightly more than the average balance of the customers staying back with the bank.
  • Data contains only 20% of customers who left the bank indicating an imbalance in the data.

We determined that recall is the metric of interest as we want minimal False Negatives.

We prepped the data for Model Building.

  • Used OneHotEncoding for encoding the 2 categorical columns - Gender and Geography.
  • We also used StandardScalar to ensure the features were in the same range.
  • Dropped the 3 columns that do not contribute to the prediction power of the model.

We built 4 models with varying configurations. All the 4 models yeilded similar loss and accuracy values. However since recall is the metric of interest, we are recommending Model2 which produced the best recall value of 0.80.

Configuration of Model 2

  • 3 layers - relu activation function for the hidden layer and sigmoid activation for the output layer.
  • Adam Optimizer with a learning rate of 0.001
  • Threshold of 0.16 was determined using the ROC-AUC curve
  • Dropout(0.5)
  • batch_size=128

Recommendations

Its obvious that customers who purchased 3 or 4 products are the ones who are leaving the bank. There is an urgent need to identify the product(s) that are causing the churn. Once identified, the bank needs to gather customer feedback on the products and build on enhancing the customer experience. Until this issue has been resolved, campaigns to get customers to buy more products might have to be placed on hold, with caution on the impact to the profits. The data tells us that more purchased products are contributing to the churn.

Customers from Germany seem to be churning more - we do not have enough data to analyze the underlying cause.

Older customers in the age group of 40 to 60 are leaving the bank. We need to invest in finding the root-cause here. Is the online experience discouraging older customers? Since we found out that younger customers tend to stay with the bank, we can channel our marketing towards attracting more younger customers.

Female customers are more likely to exit the bank compared to their male counter parts. This needs some investigation to get to the underlying cause.

Customers who actively use the bank services seem less likely to exit. Need to come up with creative ways to attract the customers to use the products regularly.

Giving incentives to provide customer feedback might help gather enough data to understand and analyze the loopholes.

50% of the customers are from France. The customers from Spain and Germany comprise of the remaining 50%. Bank could promote campaigns to attract more customers from Spain and Germany.

Bank can review customer profiles and issue credit cards to the customers that do not own a credit card. CreditScore and EstimatedSalary data can aid in customer profiling. Bank can offer promotions (lower interest rates etc) to retain the customers that are likely to leave.

We got enough data points to devise segmentation based marketing. Perhaps the bank could leverage this.

Overall, more data points can be added to the dataset to improve the prediction capabilities.
